  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The forthcoming article, titled \"G-protein-coupled receptor diversity and evolution in the closest living relatives of metazoa,\" showcases significant research supported by the Human Frontier Science Program and involves leading institutions, such as the Howard Hughes Medical Institute. Although the study is currently in preprint with no citations yet, it underscores a commitment to open science practices by sharing findings with the academic community ahead of formal publication.</p>\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The article authored by Alain Garcia De Las Bayonas and Nicole King, titled \"G-protein-coupled receptor diversity and evolution in the closest living relatives of metazoa,\" addresses critical aspects of evolutionary biology and receptor diversity. Set to be published in eLife in 2025, the work is underpinned by a robust institutional framework, being affiliated with the Howard Hughes Medical Institute, a notable institution in biological research. This strong institutional backing highlights the significance of the topic being explored.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Research in this area is largely funded by the Human Frontier Science Program, reflecting a broader institutional investment in understanding the evolution of metazoan biology. Such funding not only validates the relevance of the research but also signifies collaborative efforts within the scientific community aimed at unraveling complex biological processes.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Currently available as a preprint, the authors have embraced open science practices, granting early access to their findings. Although there are no metrics available regarding downloads or citations yet, this preprint facilitates immediate engagement with the academic community, potentially influencing ongoing research discussions in the field. Sharing preliminary results offers a chance for feedback and refinement as the research advances toward formal publication.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">In terms of data accessibility, the article mentions the use of data repositories like Figshare and Crossref Dataset Citation. This commitment to open data is crucial for fostering transparency and reproducibility within the field, enabling other researchers to build upon this foundational work. Although there are currently no public discussions or citations associated with the preprint, the ongoing study promises to contribute valuable insights into G-protein-coupled receptor evolution and diversity, enriching our understanding of metazoan relatives.</p>",
